				 																																																				London: Andy Roddick will lead the US against defending champions Russia in the Davis Cup final. The sixth-ranked Roddick, who has never won a Davis Cup title, was selected along with No. 13 James Blake and the top-ranked doubles pair of Bob and Mike Bryan. The best-of-five tie will be played from November 30 to December 2 on the indoor hard courts of the Memorial Coliseum in Portland, Oregon. The Russian team, which won their second Davis Cup title last year, will be led by No. 4 Nikolay Davydenko, Igor Andreev, Dmitry Tursunov and Mikhail Youzhny, the International Tennis Federation announced on Tuesday.				 																																																				Frankfurt: IBF champion Wladimir Klitschko and WBO titleholder Sultan Ibragimov will fight February 23 in Madison Square Garden to unify two of the four heavyweight world titles, Klitschkos management said Tuesday. Regarded by many as the best of the current heavyweights, Klitschko (49-3, 44 knockouts) tops the independent IBO rankings. Ibragimov (22-0-1, 17 knockouts) pounded out a unanimous decision against Evander Holyfield last month.				 																																																				Holyfield lost heavyweight boxings last unification fight in 1999, dropping his WBA and IBF belts to WBC champion Lennox Lewis.				 																																																				Hobart: Olympic gold medal-winning swimmer Brooke Hanson announced her retirement on Tuesday. The 29-year-old Australian said she had decided to quit after struggling to rediscover her motivation since suffering an electric shock in a spa pool earlier this year. I now know that my heart, my mind and my body have decided it is time for the next chapter in my life, she told reporters.				 																																																				Hanson won a silver medal in the 100m breaststroke at the 2004 Athens Olympics and was also awarded a gold for swimming a heat for the Australian team that won the 4x100 medley relay. She was named outstanding female swimmer at the short-course World Championships in Indianapolis in 2004 after winning a record six titles.				 																																																				Thun: Six current and three former FC Thun soccer players were charged Tuesday for allegedly having sexual relations with a minor. Five other individuals, who are not soccer players, also face charges, the office of the investigating magistrate of the Bernese Alps said. Police of canton Bern last week temporarily arrested a dozen FC Thun players and others on suspicion of having sex with a 15-year-old girl. Most of the suspects acknowledged they had sexual relations with the girl, the magistrates office said.				 																																																				London: Referee Danny McDermid has been cleared of using abusive language toward Leeds manager Dennis Wise. 				 																																																				New York: World champions Tyson Gay and Allyson Felix were named winners of the 2007 Jesse Owens Award on Monday as the sports top US athletes, USA Track amp; Field (USATF) announced. Gay sprinted to the 100m and 200m world titles and led the US to the 4x100m relay gold at the IAAF championships in Osaka. He also ran the second-fastest 200m of all time, 19.62 seconds, at the American Championships, where he won the sprint double.				 																																																																																		 Athletics: IAAF World Championships H/Ls from 5.30pm on Neo Sports Plus
